        <p class="content text-right" id="degree-content">
    Aside from adjacency, each vertex in a graph has a <em>degree</em>.
    For any vertex <var>U</var>, the <em>degree</em> is equal to the number of vertices adjacent to <var>U</var>.
    In the graph on the left, the degree of vertex <var>A</var> is one because vertex <var>A</var> is adjacent to vertex <var>B</var>.
    The degree of vertex <var>B</var> is two because vertex <var>B</var> is adjacent to both vertices <var>A</var> and <var>C</var>.
    Vertex <var>D</var>, on the other hand, has a degree of zero because <var>D</var> is adjacent to no vertex.
        </p>
